6 Section 1. Section 2-15-501, MCA, is amended to read:
7 "2-15-501. General duties. It is the duty of the attorney general:
8 (1) to prosecute or defend all causes in the supreme court:
9 (a) in which the state or any officer of the state in the officer's official capacity is a party; or
10 (b) in which the state has an interest;, subject to subsections (1)(b)(i) through (1)(b)(v).
11 (i) At least 10 business days prior to engaging in litigation in which the state may have an interest,
12 the attorney general shall produce a statement of intent to engage in litigation in the interest of the state, which
13 must be provided to the governor's office and the house and senate judiciary committees or, in the interim, the
14 law and justice interim committee, and published on the department of justice website. The statement of intent
15 must include:
16 (A) the nature and location of the proposed litigation;
17 (B) the nature of the state's interest;
18 (C) the attorney general's position on the issues; and
19 (D) an itemized projection of costs to the state for engaging in the litigation.
20 (ii) When notice of intent has been provided, the attorney general shall schedule a public hearing
21 with at least 5 business days' notice and provide an opportunity for comment from the public concerning the
22 attorney general's proposed litigation before engaging in litigation in which the state may have an interest.
23 (iii) The attorney general shall fully consider any written submissions and public comments when
24 deciding whether to proceed with litigation in the interest of the state. The attorney general's decision and a
25 statement responding to the written submissions and public comments made during the hearing must be posted
26 on the department of justice website within 5 business days of the public hearing and prior to the attorney
27 general engaging in litigation.
28 (iv) In a bona fide emergency in which time is of the essence or other circumstance that demands
